<br>
#1 First and foremost, you need resistances. fire resist is the most commonly needed, and if your short of 140 resist your hopelessly screwed and a burden on your healer. (Yes I know about the buggy ToV dragons but I'm not going into those) Alot of dragons have fire AE's, and it does hurt. Cold is also important, to a lesser degree, and suprisingly few dragons use it. Disease and poison are for special dragon ancounters. The weakest of these dragons that fall into this catergory is Trakanon. 130 poison resist means you resist most of his AE's. He's a wuss anyways. Other dragons such as Hoshkgar will own you with their AE's alone, and you need a full bag specifically for poison/disease gear. Magic resist is only important if the dragon your fighting has the lure based AE fear (Wuoshi, talendor, gorenaire, Sontalak) but you just dont need to bother if its just DragonFear1, which is easily shrugged off and no worse than a fear trap in the necropolis. If your getting feared, you arent tanking, so buff this up if your going to need it. My usual resist package has about 140 dis/poison, 160 fire, 170 cold, and over 200 magic resist.<br>
<br>
#2 Armor - AC just doesnt mean very much against dragons such as Yelinak and Klandikar. They're going to do maximum damage to you on most strikes anyways, so I opt for things that add hit points. A total Ac tank at level 60 would have around 4700 hit points, whereas a smart tank using a suit to add +hps can have right at 6k. That's with 255 stamina, and around +500 hps tacked on from gear. the more you have, the more efficient complete heals are. I use that setup and still come out with over 1220 AC.<br>
<br>
#3 - Staying alive. If you get below 3 bubbles, back off and get a heal. Only a fool stays in there. Unless its a really wimpy dragon like Wuoshi or Serverrilous, you cannot tank dragons. Even under defensive, you usually take dmg faster than your clerics(s) can keep up with, so back out and let someone else take the heat. If you havent burned your discipline yet and suddenly get locked onto by the dragon, and know your about to die because your heal isn't going to land in time, hit the /dis furious or /dis fortitude hotkey. You may be less efficient for the rest of the fight than a warrior running defensive, but at least your not dead, and your cleric has time to heal you. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#989dca><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub41.ezboard.com/ukjice.showPublicProfile?language=EN>KJ ICE</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>EC Pimp</span><br>  Posts: 25<br> <font color=#333333>(5/28/01 10:17:49 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: How to stay alive in dragon encounters.</span><hr size=1>  I've been trying to read as much about Severilious as I can, and I've heard he has a poison-based aoe stun? Got a good number to shoot for on resists with him?<br>
<br>
 I haven't been on dragon raids aside from Naggy and Ragefire, but insta-cast items like Shrunken Gobby Earrings are a great way to preserve your buffs. Once he aoe dispels, just right click and its back up. Dunno if this holds true for the Velious dragons or not.<br>
